es, and thus enables not only a detailed examination of GDR socialisation, but crucially also its influence in unified Germany. Anna Saunders explores the extent to which a young generation’s loyalties can be officially regulated in the face of cultural and historical traditions, changing material conditions and shifting social circumstances, and finds GDR socialisation to be influential to post-unification loyalties through its impact on the personal sphere, rather than through the official sphere of ideological propaganda. At a time of globalisation, this lucid study not only provides unique insight into the functioning of the GDR state and its longer-term impact, but also advances our broader understanding of the ways in which collective loyalties are formed. It will be of particular interest to those in the fields of German History and Politics, European Studies and Sociology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPatriotismzGermany (East)xHistory. 0aPolitical socializationzGermany (East)xHistory. 0aSocialism and youthzGermany (East)xHistory. 0aYouthxPolitical activityzGermany (East)xHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh  aBerlin Wall.  aGDR.  aGerman Democratic Republic.  acollective loyalties.  aideological propaganda.  apost-unification loyalties.  asocialisation.  asocialist patriotic education.  astate rhetoric.  aunified Germany.1 aSaunders, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779443740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847794437423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847794437/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packag